Class InjectiveEnumMap<K extends java.lang.Enum<K>,V>

  • java.lang.Object

  • Type Parameters:
    K - The type of the keys held by this map.
    V - The (enum) type of the values held by this map.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    InjectiveMap<K,V>, java.util.Map<K,V>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    InjectiveBiEnumMap, InjectiveEnumHashMap

    public class InjectiveEnumMap<K extends java.lang.Enum<K>,V>
extends GenericInjectiveMap<K,V>
    The InjectiveEnumMap is an injective map whose key values are constants from a specific enum instance. More specifically, an java.util.EnumMap is used to hold the key-to-value mappings, so all of the advantages (and quirks) of that class are inherited here. As the value-to-key mapping is not defined in this class, this class should generally be used to construct more specific injective maps using enums as their key type.
    See Also:
    InjectiveEnumHashMap, InjectiveBiEnumMap

      • determineEnumClassFromMap

        protected static <K extends java.lang.Enum<K>> java.lang.Class<K> determineEnumClassFromMap(java.util.Map<K,?> map)
        Determine the enum class which whose elements are used as the keys for a specified map. If the map is not an InjectiveEnumMap instance, then the map must be non-empty (have at least one entry) so that the enum type of the map can be inferred.
        Parameters:
        map - The input map from which the key enum class will be determined.
        Returns:
        the enum class whose elements are used as keys in map.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if map is empty and not an InjectiveEnumMap instance.
